      <hedline>
        <hl1>Helicopters in Combat</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>James Eisenberg letter disputes October 20 article on Israel's use of attack helicopters in response to violence in West Bank and Gaza</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Israel has been wrongly criticized for using attack helicopters in response to the violence in the West Bank and Gaza (news article, Oct. 20). Picture an apartment building as a huge concrete bunker with numerous concealed firing positions. Now picture the double and triple cross-fire that soldiers would face trying to move, murderously slow and exposed, along a street packed with buildings.  The attack helicopter, on the other hand, is fast, highly maneuverable and provides instant high ground.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Israel has been wrongly criticized for using attack helicopters in response to the violence in the West Bank and Gaza (news article, Oct. 20). Picture an apartment building as a huge concrete bunker with numerous concealed firing positions. Now picture the double and triple cross-fire that soldiers would face trying to move, murderously slow and exposed, along a street packed with buildings.  The attack helicopter, on the other hand, is fast, highly maneuverable and provides instant high ground.</p>
        <p>An enemy can hide behind the shield of a crowded neighborhood, taking advantage of our sensibility to limit collateral damage, and render our smart bombs useless. The attack helicopter, picking targets accurately and with discrimination, evens the odds.</p>
        <p>JAMES EISENBERG  Ithaca, N.Y., Oct. 20, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is an Army captain.</p>
      </block>
